# agent-pods runtime config — copy to ~/.config/pod/config.sh and edit.
# This is a PLAIN SHELL FILE, sourced by every pod-* script via _pod-paths.sh.
# Set only what you want to override; anything you omit keeps its built-in default.
# (The agent CATALOG is separate — that's adapters/*.toml + ~/.config/pod/slots.toml.)

# --- deck identity -------------------------------------------------------------
# New pods are named after a random free city (Rome, Kyoto, ...); the numeric
# <prefix>, <prefix>-2, ... series is the fallback when the city pool is exhausted.
# POD_SESSION_PREFIX=pod
# POD_CITIES=        # override the city pool (space-separated single-word names)

# Window 0 is the "manager". By default it becomes the best agent you actually have
# installed, in POD_MANAGER_PREFER order, launched with that agent's default
# model/effort — and only falls back to a shell (showing the `pod` roster) if NONE of
# those agents are present. Override the order, or pin a specific manager:
#   POD_MANAGER_PREFER="claude-code codex cursor openclaw"   # default; first installed wins
#   POD_MANAGER_CMD=claude          # pin the manager to a specific command (skips auto-pick)
#   POD_MANAGER_CARD="Claude Code · opus · manager"
# Set POD_MANAGER_CMD to a shell to FORCE the plain manager seat regardless of agents:
#   POD_MANAGER_CMD=/bin/bash
# POD_MANAGER_NAME=manager
# POD_MANAGER_PREFER="claude-code codex cursor openclaw"
# POD_MANAGER_CMD=
# When FULL AUTO is on, the manager window is renamed to signal the mode. Defaults to
# POD_MANAGER_NAME (a visible no-op); set a distinct name to make the switch obvious:
# POD_MANAGER_NAME_AUTO=

# --- gold stars ----------------------------------------------------------------
# Stars are HUMAN-only. This name is attributed in the award log + the delivered
# prompt ("Gold star from <name>!"). Defaults to "the human".
# POD_STAR_AWARDER="the human"

# --- state location ------------------------------------------------------------
# All ephemeral state lives under one tmp tree. Override the base if /tmp is unusual.
# POD_TMP=/tmp/pod

# --- tmux binary ---------------------------------------------------------------
# Empty -> resolved on PATH. Set an absolute path only if tmux isn't on PATH for
# non-interactive shells.
# POD_TMUX=

# --- foreign-state poller (state dot for agents without lifecycle hooks) --------
# POD_FOREIGN_INTERVAL=3     # seconds between idle/busy polls
# POD_FOREIGN_TRIM=8         # bottom lines (input box + footer) excluded from the hash

# --- one-line agent summaries (@summary, shown in pod / pod-summary / the journal) --
# pod-summarize turns an agent's recent output into a one-line "what it's doing"
# label. Tier 1 is free and always on: an explicit <!-- STATUS: "..." --> tag in the
# agent's own output wins verbatim (teach your agents the tag and you need nothing
# else). Tier 2 is OFF by default: set POD_SUMMARIZE_CMD to any shell command that
# reads recent output on stdin and prints ONE short line — a small local model, or an
# agent CLI in print mode, e.g.:
#   POD_SUMMARIZE_CMD='claude -p "Summarize what this agent is doing in one short present-tense line, no preamble."'
# POD_SUMMARIZE_CMD=
# POD_SUMMARIZE_TIMEOUT=45         # kill a wedged summarizer after this many seconds
# POD_SUMMARIZE_MIN_INTERVAL=120   # poller-triggered (foreign-agent) rate limit, seconds

# --- FULL AUTO celebration -------------------------------------------------------
# The ⚡ popup animation when a pod's FULL AUTO switch flips ON. Cosmetic, skippable
# with any key. Set POD_AUTO_ANIM=0 to disable, POD_AUTO_HOLD to change its length.
# POD_AUTO_ANIM=1
# POD_AUTO_HOLD=4

# --- queue module (modules/queue) ------------------------------------------------
# When a mgr-poll sweep finds the queue fully drained, workers whose task just
# completed are closed (window killed + deregistered) so finished agents don't pile
# up idle. Guarded (never the manager, never a busy/wait window). 0 disables.
# MGR_REAP_FINISHED_WORKERS=1
